Chirac's death and his political legacy lives on
On the 26th local time, former French President Jacques Chirac died suddenly at the age of 86.
At a time when the world is undergoing major changes unseen in a century, the many political legacies left by this French politician when he was in power are still worthy of our praise.
Jacques Chirac served as president of France for 12 years in a charismatic manner.
He not only inherited the independent diplomatic spirit of Gaullistism, but also firmly supported European integration, and was a representative figure of pursuing the "European dream".
At the same time, he also vigorously advocated multipolarization and multilateralism in the world, and was a politician with strategic vision.
For this reason, the French press described him as "an outstanding representative of France on the world stage".
One of Chirac's most talked-about political decisions was to oppose the U.S.-led war in Iraq.
Under his leadership, France and Germany withstood American pressure and were at the forefront of the anti-war effort.
A year after the war began, he predicted that the war in Iraq would lead to an increase in terror and make the world more dangerous.
Chirac's warning proved to be correct.
At a time when European integration is in turmoil and US unilateralism is becoming more and more prominent, Chirac's strategic thinking and choices on international politics and global affairs are undoubtedly of great enlightening significance.
Chirac is also a French politician who is familiar and familiar to Chinese.
He is one of the advocates and creators of the "golden decade" of Sino-French relations, and after being elected president of France for the first time in 1995, he has promoted the rapid development of Sino-French relations with the strategic vision of a statesman.
In 2004, China and France established a comprehensive strategic partnership, marking a new stage in bilateral exchanges.
During Chirac's administration, bilateral trade between China and France grew rapidly, and breakthroughs were made in cooperation between the two countries in aviation, nuclear energy, railway transportation and other fields.
The Sino-French Year of Culture initiated by Jacques Chirac has created a new model of cultural exchange in the history of China and France.
Chirac's lifelong love of Chinese culture was particularly impressive.
According to Chinese diplomats who know him, Chirac can recite some poems of Li Bai and Du Fu, and can even accurately judge the historical age of Chinese bronzes.
"If you don't look at the pyramids, you won't really be to Egypt, and if you don't look at the Qin figurines, you'll not really be to China" -- this golden phrase comes from Jacques Chirac.
In an exclusive interview with Xinhua News Agency, Jacques Chirac said: "The West has concerns about China's political and social development, the ecological problems caused by China's economic growth, and China's international political position.
But I myself have full confidence in China.
I believe that China is a country with a long history of civilization, and its experience is sufficient to help it establish the concept and values of harmonious development and shoulder its responsibilities on the world stage for a long time. ”
I also believe that China's rejuvenation will bring new creative vitality to world culture and enrich world culture.
The Sri Lankan people are gone, but Chirac's legacy and revelations to the world will live on.
