Be cautious of using plastic tea bags to make tea!
According to the "Central News Agency", recently, a new study in Canada found that a pack of plastic tea bags may release billions, or even tens of billions of microplastics, significantly higher than the amount of microplastics a person is estimated to ingest throughout the year, but so far there is no evidence that ingesting microplastics poses a threat to humans.
According to reports, researchers at Magill University in Canada have found that dipping a plastic tea bag into a cup of almost boiling hot water (95 degrees Celsius) releases about 11.6 billion microplastics and 3.1 billion smaller nanomicroplastics into the cup.
This amount is significantly higher than the amount of microplastics a person is estimated to ingest throughout the year.
According to a study published earlier in 2019, the average person eats at least 50,000 microplastics per year and inhales the same amount of microplastics at the same time.
It is reported that the study was published in the Journal of Environmental Science and Technology, and the researchers tested four different types of plastic commercial tea bags in Montreal stores and cafes, opened the tea bags, washed the tea bags and immersed them in almost boiling water for 5 minutes, and then analyzed them with an electron microscope and spectrometer.
According to the study, they found that more than 11.6 billion microplastics were released from a single tea bag, which was "several orders higher than the previous plastic load of other foods".
According to the report, most tea bags are made of natural fibers, but many brands that use natural fibers to make tea bags still use plastic to seal them.
Some brands of tea bags have moved away from paper and have switched to plastic, which the researchers tested.
Microplastics are tiny fragments of plastic that researchers define to be between 100 nanometers and 5 millimeters in size and are mainly produced by the decomposition of plastic waste.
Researchers have found traces of microplastics in the air, soil, rivers and deepest ocean trenches around the world, as well as in tap water, bottled water, seafood and beer.
In October 2018, researchers first found microplastics in human fecal samples from several countries in different regions of the world.
To test the potential toxicity of microplastics released from tea bags, the Canadian team put Daphnia in contaminated water and found that microplastics affect the behavior of these Daphnia and cause them to develop malformations.
According to the World Health Organization (WHO), there is no evidence to date that ingestion of microplastics poses a threat to humans.
However, the WHO notes that more research is needed to fully understand how these plastics spread into the environment and what the impact is on humans.
The researchers speculate that the reason for the release of large amounts of microplastics in these tea bags may be that these plastic tea bags come into contact with boiling water, which can decompose or leach toxic substances even when the "food grade" plastic is heated above 40 degrees Celsius.
Guterres said the climate emergency is the biggest threat to the survival of small island states.
There, a natural disaster can erode the development gains of a generation.
This is illustrated by the hurricane-scarred events of Barbuda, Dominica and the Bahamas this year.
About a quarter of people in small island developing States live at an altitude of 5 metres or less.
Relocation can have serious social and lifestyle implications, and even raise questions of sovereignty and national identity.
At this Monday's Climate Action Summit, small island states are once again leading the way in the right direction by their shared commitment to achieve carbon neutrality and 100% renewable energy by 2030.
Guterres said: "The climate crisis is piling new injustices on top of old ones.
Although small island developing States contribute little to global warming, they pay the highest price.
Because of their middle-income status, many are also trapped in an accelerated and unsustainable cycle of disasters and debt.
The world must act, and now is the time to make big decisions and invest heavily in small island developing States. ”
Today's high-level meeting adopted a political declaration calling for ways to help small island developing States manage disaster risk, invest in climate-resilient infrastructure and transition to renewable energy, and urge international agencies to help small island developing States, particularly heavily indebted middle-income countries, access finance.
Small island developing States are at the forefront of protecting and conserving the lifeblood of the planet – the oceans.
The latest special report released this week by the Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change confirms that the oceans are already suffering the "sweeping in" consequences of the climate crisis.
By mid-century, many regions are likely to experience some of the most extreme sea-level rises that would otherwise occur once in a century each year.
The report warns that some island nations are likely to become uninhabitable without significant investment in adaptation.
Pollution, overfishing, and acidification have taken their toll.
In the last 150 years, the world has lost half of all living corals, and plastic pollution has increased tenfold in the last 40 years.
Demands from industry, shipping, mining and tourism are leading to dwindling resources, including the maintenance of fishing grounds for many island communities.
Small island states also face high costs for transport, energy and infrastructure.
They are heavily dependent on a number of external markets, making them subject to price fluctuations.
Some States are also grappling with the security implications of illicit trafficking in persons, arms and drugs.
Guterres said: "By solving a problem in the most challenging environment, that problem can be solved anywhere.
The efforts of small island developing States to achieve the 2030 Agenda for Sustainable Development will provide us with tools, lessons learned and examples that the world can learn from. ”
He stressed that small island developing States were a special case of sustainable development.
They require the long-term attention and investment of the entire international community.
