The main shaft of the deepest shaft of China's railway is excavated to the end.
Kunming, Xinhua News Agency, September 27 (Reporter Ding Yiquan) According to China Railway Tunnel Bureau Group Co., Ltd., the main shaft of the No. 1 shaft of the Gaoligongshan Tunnel of the Dali Rui (Li) Railway was successfully excavated to the end on the 27th, with a depth of 762.59 meters, breaking the record for the deepest railway shaft in China.
In tunnel construction, the shaft can play a role in improving tunnel ventilation, improving ballast efficiency, and ensuring construction safety.
Song Tao, chief engineer of the shaft work area of the Darui Project Department of China Railway Tunnel Bureau, said: "After the successful excavation of the main shaft of the No. 1 shaft of the Gaoligongshan Tunnel, it will help to promote the construction of the underground parking lot, open multiple working faces for the later construction of the main tunnel and flat guide, and speed up the construction progress of the entire Gaoligongshan Tunnel. ”
Song Tao introduced that the construction of the No. 1 shaft of the Gaoligongshan Tunnel adopts the sinking method, which is equipped with a sinking derrick, a sinking stable car, a sinking winch, an overall moving metal formwork, an FJD-6A umbrella drill, a central rotary rock grabber and other large-scale specialized machinery, forming a mechanized excavation system, ballast system, suspension system, winch lifting system and other "four-in-one" mechanized assembly line, realizing the whole process of mechanized operations such as drilling, blasting, ballasting, formwork installation, concrete pouring, etc., which greatly accelerates the construction progress.
It is understood that the Dali Railway starts from Dali in the east to Ruili in the west, with a total length of about 331 kilometers and a design speed of 140 kilometers per hour, which is an important part of the China-Myanmar international railway channel.
With a total length of 34.538 kilometers, the Gaoligongshan Tunnel is the longest railway tunnel in China.
