Study: The U.S. National Healthy Diet Index Grows Slightly, but Remains Challenge-Chinanews.com
Chinanews.com, September 27 According to a report by the Overseas Chinese News Network in the United States, a recent study in the United States showed that in the past 16 years, the healthy diet index of the US government has increased moderately, from 56 to 58.
But with a perfect score of 100, it's not something to celebrate.
The U.S. people still face "significant challenges" when it comes to diet.
Dr. Fangfang Zhang, a nutrition researcher at Tufts University in Massachusetts and one of the study's authors, said Americans are still consuming too much food that can trigger heart disease, diabetes, obesity and other diseases, which are the most common diseases in the United States.
The study was published in the Journal of the American Medical Association on the 24th.
The study is based on the findings of a health survey of 44,000 adults conducted by the U.S. government from 1999 to 2016.
The authors write that "despite the considerable improvements, significant dietary challenges remain".
It is reported that these challenges include getting the American people to reduce their intake of snacks, hot dogs, fat beef, butter and other foods containing saturated fat.
The study found that people's daily dietary intake of these unhealthy fats increased from 11.5% to 12%, exceeding the recommended upper limit of 10%.
The biggest improvement in the U.S. diet has been the reduction in sugar intake from 16 percent to about 14 percent, but the intake is still too high.
Officially, the daily diet should contain less than 10% of added sugars.
Researchers believe that the reason for the decrease in sugar intake is related to the decrease in people's consumption of sweetened sodas, but Zhang stressed that sugars are often added to even less sweet foods, such as yogurt and ketchup.
U.S. adults have a small increase in their intake of fruits, nuts, oats, and other whole grain groups.
However, data from 2016 shows that these foods still account for less than 5% of the daily diet.
Although people consume a little less salt and drink less fruit juice leads to a lower intake of low-quality carbohydrates, Zhang says they still account for up to 42 percent of daily calories, many of which come from refined white bread and other refined grains.
The study is based on biennial personal health surveys that ask adults to recall the foods they have eaten in the past 24 hours.
Since 2003, these health surveys have asked this question twice every few days.
The government's dietary guidelines for U.S. residents recommend that people adopt a "healthy eating pattern" to reduce the likelihood of chronic disease.
The guidelines state that people should eat more nutrient-dense foods, such as vegetables, fruits, whole grains, low-fat dairy products, and seafood, lean meat, poultry, eggs, and seeds that can provide protein.
The number of Americans with diabetes nearly doubled to more than 7 percent during the study period, and obesity rates increased over the years between the study — about 70 percent of U.S. adults are now overweight or obese.
In addition, heart disease remains the leading cause of death for U.S. nationals.
