The record for the deepest railway tunnel shaft in China has been refreshed
Baoshan, China-Singapore Baoshan, September 27 (Zhang Weiming, Xu Weiguo, Zhou Jingbo) After more than 1,200 days of day and night construction, the No. 1 shaft of the Gaoligongshan Tunnel of the Dali (Li) Rui (Li) Railway under construction was completed on the 27th, with a depth of 762.59 meters below the ground, breaking the record for the deepest railway tunnel shaft in China, and this record was created under the condition of a large amount of water.
The 34.5-kilometer-long Gaoligongshan Tunnel of the Dalui Railway is located in Yunnan, and the tunnel crosses the Gaoligongshan Mountains from the west bank of the Nujiang River, making it the longest double-track single-hole tunnel in Asia.
The tunnel passes through 19 fault zones and is buried to a maximum depth of 1,155 meters, because it covers almost all the undesirable geology and major risks that may be encountered in tunnel construction, and the Gaoligongshan Tunnel is known as the "geological museum" of tunnel construction.
The shaft is the most important auxiliary tunnel of the Gaoligongshan Tunnel, which shoulders the important task of increasing the working surface to achieve "long tunnel and short fighting" and ventilation of railway operation in the later stage.
The No. 1 shaft was successfully excavated to the bottom of the shaft, marking the official entry of the Gaoligongshan Tunnel into the horizontal tunnel construction, and after the excavation of the underground parking lot and the replacement of equipment, 4 working faces can be added underground to speed up the excavation of the tunnel.
"The shafts are all in the granite formation, because there are many cracks in the granite formation, the water can't be stopped, and the flow from top to bottom is non-stop, basically how deep the well is, how big the water pressure is. ”
Si Jingzhao, chief engineer of the Dalui Railway Project Department of China Railway Tunnel Bureau, told reporters that during the construction of the shaft, there were many dangerous situations such as mud inrush and collapse, and the construction party invited experts to take the pulse on the spot and discussed the treatment plan more than 20 times.
"The water inflow in the shaft is at its maximum, reaching more than 300 cubic meters per hour, and the bottom of the shaft is more than 700 meters deep, and the water pressure is equivalent to the seabed at a depth of 700 meters. ”
Si Jingzhao said, "If we don't pump and drain water in time, the well will be flooded 10 meters in one hour, and we spend almost 85% of our time controlling water and 15% of our time excavating." ”
In order to overcome the geological problems such as the development of longitudinal joints, mud inrush and water-rich granite in the surrounding rock of Shaft 1, the tunnel construction adopts systematic water control measures combining "exploration, injection and excavation" to reduce the construction risk.
After many improvements, the construction of No. 1 shaft has formed mechanized assembly lines such as excavation system, ballast system, suspension system, and winch hoisting system, which has realized the whole process of mechanized operations such as drilling, blasting, ballasting, formwork installation, and concrete pouring, and accelerated the construction progress.
In the end, after more than 1,200 days and nights of construction, the shaft was successfully excavated to a depth of 762.59 meters.
With a total length of 330 kilometers, the Dalui Railway is an important part of the China-Myanmar International Corridor and an important transportation infrastructure for the implementation of the "Belt and Road" construction.
After the completion and opening to traffic, the driving time from Dali to Ruili will be shortened from 6 hours to 2 hours, which will greatly improve the transportation pattern in western Yunnan and promote economic and trade cooperation and friendly personnel exchanges between China and South and Southeast Asian countries.
Carrie Lam: As a Chinese, we are proud of our country's achievements
Hong Kong's press circles celebrate the 70th anniversary of the founding of the People's Republic of China.
The "Hong Kong Press Reception to Celebrate the 70 th Anniversary of the Founding of the People's Republic of China" was held in Hong Kong on 27 July.
Carrie Lam, Chief Executive of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region, pointed out in her speech at the reception that the achievements of our country in the past 70 years are obvious to the world, and we as Chinese are proud of it.
Carrie Lam, Deputy Director of the Liaison Office of the Central People's Government in the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region Lu Xinning, Deputy Commissioner of the Office of the Commissioner of the Ministry of Foreign Affairs in Hong Kong Song Ruan, Deputy Political Commissar of the People's Liberation Army Hong Kong Garrison Chen Yading, and Chairman of the Executive Committee of the Preparatory Committee for the Celebration of the National Day of the Hong Kong Press Jiang Zaizhong attended the reception and officiated at the reception.
Carrie Lam pointed out in her speech that in the past 70 years, China has forged ahead, and although it has faced many difficulties and challenges, it has overcome and surpassed them one by one, and the achievements it has made are obvious to the world, and we as Chinese are proud of it.
Since Hong Kong's return to the motherland, it has been closely linked with the mainland, working hand in hand to make progress and share fruitful results.
It is believed that under the premise of "One Country, Two Systems", Hong Kong can continue to leverage its advantages in the future, seize the opportunities arising from the Belt and Road Initiative and the Guangdong-Hong Kong-Macao Greater Bay Area, and seek a better future for Hong Kong.
She also said that in the past few months, there have been many social controversies in Hong Kong, which has affected everyone in Hong Kong and faced different challenges for journalists.
At this critical juncture, I hope that friends in the media will continue to rise to the challenge, uphold professionalism, make fair and fair news reports for the society, and contribute to the future of Hong Kong and the return of the society to rational communication and dialogue.
In his speech, Jiang Zaizhong pointed out that the glorious course that New China has traversed is also a course of common development, common progress, blood ties, and weal and woe between Hong Kong and the motherland.
