Iran has been confirmed to have developed advanced centrifuges and further suspended the implementation of the JCPOA
Chinanews.com, September 27 According to the "Central News Agency", the United Nations International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA) said on the 26th that Iran has once again violated the JCPOA by using advanced centrifuges to make enriched uranium.
Iran is reportedly progressively violating JCPOA restrictions in response to US President Donald Trump's withdrawal from the JCPOA in May 2018 and reinstatement and tightening sanctions on Iran.
Iran has suspended two other commitments in July, namely to keep its stocks of enriched uranium below 300 kilograms and to enrich uranium to no more than 3.67 percent pure, and is now taking it further.
Under the nuclear deal, Iran will be able to accumulate enriched uranium by installing only about 5,000 first-generation IR-1 centrifuges in Natanz, and will only allow Iran to use a small number of more advanced models for research purposes, but will not produce enriched uranium.
If Iran succeeds in developing more advanced centrifuges, it will be able to produce enriched uranium several times faster, potentially for use in the manufacture of nuclear bombs.
According to the report, the IAEA report states: "On September 25, the agency confirmed that Iran has developed advanced centrifuges of Model 2 and Model 3... Accumulation or preparation for accumulation of enriched uranium. ”
The United Nations International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA) presented the report to member states on the 26th, and a diplomat responded: "They are busy on the (Natanz enriched uranium) facility." ”
