China's development is an opportunity for the world, not a threat or challenge.
(70 Years of the People's Republic of China) White Paper: China's development is an opportunity for the world, not a threat or challenge.
The white paper points out that China's development is an opportunity for the world, not a threat or challenge.
The white paper says that with the rapid increase of China's comprehensive national strength and international influence, some people in the international community are worried that China will take the path of "a strong country must be hegemonic," and some people have put forward the so-called "China threat theory."
This is not only a cognitive misreading, but also a deep-rooted prejudice, a psychological imbalance caused by the growth and decline of power, and a deliberate distortion to protect one's own vested interests.
Realizing national prosperity and strength, national rejuvenation and people's happiness is not only the dream of the Chinese people, but also the common dream of the people of all countries.
"China's development is an opportunity for the world, not a threat or challenge. ”
The white paper points out that China is the main stabilizer and power source of world economic growth, China is the largest contributor to world economic growth, China's scientific and technological innovation has injected new momentum into world economic growth, and the role of China's economy as a stabilizer and power source in the future will be more prominent.
At present, the world's economic growth momentum is insufficient, and a stable Chinese economy is becoming more and more important to the world.
China's economy is shifting from high-speed growth to high-quality development, with new industrialization, informatization, urbanization, and agricultural modernization accelerating, in-depth adjustment of the economic structure, continuous upgrading of industrial optimization, and the emergence of new economic growth points.
According to a research report by the McKinsey Global Institute, by 2040, the integration of China and the rest of the world's economies is expected to create $22 trillion to $37 trillion in economic value, equivalent to 15% to 26% of the global economy. ”
The white paper stresses that China's economy and the world economy have undergone structural changes and are deeply integrated.
China's more stable economic operation, higher quality growth, and promising growth prospects are good for the development of the world economy in the long run.
It is not feasible and harmful to regard China's economic development as a "threat" and "challenge", and to try to squeeze China out of the global industrial chain, supply chain, and value chain, so as to "decouple" China from the world economy.
The white paper points out that all-round opening-up has created more opportunities for countries to share the "China dividend".
China unswervingly pursues a mutually beneficial and win-win strategy of opening-up, and achieves greater efforts and a higher level of opening-up.
"Openness should be two-way and mutually beneficial, not one-way and mutually beneficial.
Mutual benefit and two-way can be long-term and lasting. ”
The white paper says that China is committed to continuing to expand imports, relax market access, improve the business environment, and strengthen the protection of intellectual property rights.
Only when all parties work together can we create an open, inclusive, inclusive, balanced and win-win development environment, jointly make the "cake" of development bigger and bigger, and form a mutually beneficial and win-win community of interests.
The white paper points out that China provides more public goods to the international community.
This includes promoting high-quality Belt and Road cooperation, building a platform for multilateral dialogue and cooperation, actively participating in international and regional affairs, and actively carrying out foreign assistance.
"China's development has benefited from the international community, and it has never forgotten to give back to the international community and provide more and better public goods to the international community. ”
In a recent written interview with Xinhua News Agency, Andrei Slepniov, general manager of the Russian Export Center, said that Russia is willing to strengthen cooperation with China in the economic and trade fields, further optimize the export structure, and promote the diversification of Russian exports to China.
Srepniov pointed out that forestry, machine-building and chemical industries account for a large proportion of Russia's exports to China, while at the same time, the export of agricultural products is also very important, including oil products, meat products and dairy products, as well as cereals, fish and seafood.
In recent years, Russia's exports of non-raw materials and non-energy products to China have also shown a good and stable development trend.
Talking about Russia's optimization of the structure of its exports to China, Srepniov said that Russia has set the task of expanding the export of high-tech products to meet the import needs of various countries and regions in the world, including China, for high-tech products.
In the future, the Russian side will improve financial and non-financial support measures to promote further growth in the number of high-tech enterprises.
Srepniov said that Russia is willing to export construction technology and high-tech building materials to China and develop cooperation with China in the fields of medicine and aviation manufacturing.
There is also great potential for cooperation between Russia and China in the field of urban environmental development.
He stressed that Russian products in many areas are "superior in quality and competitive in price" compared with similar Western products.
Referring to the two countries' goal of achieving a bilateral trade volume of 200 billion US dollars by 2024, Srepniov said that the fields of agriculture, machinery manufacturing, chemical industry and forestry will play an important role in achieving this goal.
The Russian side intends to diversify supplies in these areas and promote the export of deep-processed products.
He stressed that the Russian side intends to promote the entry of its exporters into the global value-added chain, of which China is one of the development directions.
Russian manufacturers in the fields of agriculture, metallurgy, oil and gas, and chemicals are well positioned to participate in this process.
At present, the two countries need to continue to deepen cooperation between enterprises, "create more Russian-Chinese joint ventures and jointly develop exports to third countries".
Srepniov said that the Russian Export Center is taking a variety of measures and services to support the export of Russian products to China through the Russian Export Credit and Investment Insurance Agency and the Export-Import Bank of Russia.
At the same time, the Russian export center will continue to deepen cooperation with relevant Chinese departments to promote more convenient access to the Chinese market for Russian goods and develop new categories of export products to China.
There has been a significant increase in the number of financial institutions using RMB for payments worldwide.
According to the latest "RMB Tracking Special Issue" released by the Society for Worldwide Interbank Financial Telecommunication (SWIFT) in London on the 26th, from July 2017 to July 2019, the number of financial institutions using RMB to pay in the world has increased significantly.
At the 2019 annual meeting of the Society for Worldwide Interbank Financial Telecommunication (SWIFT) in London, the "RMB Tracker Special Issue" released by the institution titled "Insight into the RMB from a London Perspective" showed that from July 2017 to July 2019, the number of financial institutions using RMB for payment increased by 11.31%, from 1,989 to 2,214.
Among them, Africa and the Middle East saw the largest increase in the number of financial institutions using RMB for payment, from 143 in July 2017 to 173 in July 2019, an increase of 20.98%.
According to the report, as of August 2019, the share of RMB in global payment currencies was 2.22%.
At the same time, London plays a leading role in offshore foreign exchange transactions in RMB.
According to the report, in July 2019, London's share of global RMB offshore foreign exchange transactions was 33.79%, ranking first in the world.
According to the report, London holds the number one spot in global forex trading.
In July 2019, London's share of global forex trading was 40.14%, the United States 12.93%, and France 7.67%.
