The Hong Kong Government has launched a free special training scheme to help employees who have recently been affected by the economy to tide over the difficulties
The Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (HKSAR) government announced on the 27th that it will launch a free special training program for employees who have been affected by the recent economic situation, and eligible trainees can receive a training allowance of up to HK$4,000 per month after completing the course.
There are many boutiques in Harbour City, Tsim Sha Tsui, Hong Kong, with few customers.
Affected by the recent social strife in Hong Kong, the number of visitors to Hong Kong has dropped sharply recently, and in addition to the tourism industry, the hotel, catering and retail industries have also been affected.
The Secretary for Labour and Welfare of the HKSAR Government, Mr Law Chi-kwong, and the Secretary for Commerce and Economic Development, Mr Edward Yau, met with the media on entrusting the Employees Retraining Board (ERB) to implement a special training programme and measures to support the tourism sector.
Law said that the challenges facing Hong Kong's economy are imminent and should not wait for the situation to calm down.
That's why the HKSAR Government has launched this free training programme called "Love Added Special".
According to reports, people who have lost their jobs or have been required by their employers to take unpaid leave since June 1 will have the opportunity to participate in the scheme as long as they meet the relevant requirements.
According to Law, the most important part of the courses is "vocational skills", covering 19 industries, including tourism, retail and catering, as well as some new "innovation and technology" courses and cross-industry "generic skills" courses.
The Chairman of the Employees Retraining Board, Mr Yu Pang-chun, said that the programme is free of charge and is expected to support about 10,000 people in need.
Participating trainees who complete each full-time or part-time course and have an attendance rate of 80% will receive a special allowance of up to HK$4,000 per student per month.
According to reports, the training course lasts for 2 to 3 months and is provided by about 50 training institutions, and the public can apply for the course from October 3 to March 31 next year, and each person can apply for a maximum of 4 courses.
In addition, the HKSAR Government has also announced a series of measures to support the tourism industry to tide over the difficulties.
These measures include easing the funding for the Travel Industry Council, subsidising 6,000 tourist guides to renew their licences and waiving annual fees for travel agents.
Exercise is tiring and brain-tiring?
According to Sputnik, a study of athletes has shown that the brain also shows signs of fatigue after high-intensity exercise.
The study, led by Marseas Pessiglion, an expert at the Pétier-Salpetrier hospital in France, shows that there is a subtle link between mental and physical work: both require cognitive control of activity.
Pesciglion explains: "You need to control the voluntary processes that can force yourself to stop when you have pain in your muscles and joints. ”
The study was initiated by the French National Institute of Physical Education and Sport (INSEP).
The school's specialists are responsible for guiding athletes in their preparation for the Olympic Games.
Some athletes have begun to suffer from overtraining syndrome, which is an irrepressible feeling of fatigue after a high load of exercise, unable to recover and declining performance.
INSEP asks the question: Could part of this condition be caused by nervous fatigue, the kind of nervous fatigue caused by excessive mental effort?
The study was published in the journal Current Biology.
