The central bank carried out a reverse repurchase operation of 30 billion yuan
Beijing, 27 Sep (Xinhua) -- On 27 September, the People's Bank of China launched a 30 billion yuan reverse repurchase operation in the form of interest rate bidding.
Due to the expiration of 40 billion yuan of reverse repurchase on the same day, the reverse repurchase operation of the People's Bank of China achieved a net withdrawal of 10 billion yuan.
The central bank announced that it would carry out a reverse repurchase operation of 30 billion yuan on the same day, with a period of 14 days and a winning interest rate of 2.7%.
This is the seventh consecutive working day for the PBOC to carry out a 14-day reverse repo operation.
According to the Shanghai Interbank Offered Rate (Shibor) released on the 27th, the overnight interest rate was 1.313%, down 32.4 basis points from the previous trading day, the 7-day interest rate was 2.59%, up 1.3 basis points from the previous trading day, the 14-day interest rate was 2.95%, down 1.7 basis points from the previous trading day, and the one-year interest rate was 3.048%, unchanged from the previous trading day.
Let Chinese citizens "go out" more at ease - interview with Cui Aimin, Director of the Consular Department of the Ministry of Foreign Affairs
Wherever you go, the Motherland is behind you.
On the 25th, the first short film on consular protection of the Ministry of Foreign Affairs was launched, and the sentence at the end of the short film resonated with the majority of netizens.
Cui Aimin, director of the Consular Department of the Ministry of Foreign Affairs, said in an interview with Xinhua News Agency that the film aims to further let the public feel the feelings and warmth of "diplomacy for the people", and let Chinese citizens feel that no matter where they are in the world, Chinese diplomats will lend a helping hand to them, give them help, strength and hope.
Overseas safety is no trivial matter, and every branch and leaf is always a matter of love.
Cui Aimin said that over the past 70 years, the number of Chinese citizens "going out" has increased dramatically, from "less than one million per year" before the reform and opening up to more than 100 million per year today.
According to statistics, since the 18th National Congress of the Communist Party of China, we have organized and implemented more than 10 major operations to evacuate or relocate Chinese citizens overseas, and safely evacuated more than 40,000 Chinese citizens from dangerous and volatile areas.
Accepted and coordinated the handling of about 500,000 cases of various types of help, involving nearly 1 million Chinese citizens.
In times of danger, the motherland can take you home, and the desire to go on a "walk-and-go" trip is no longer a dream.
According to Cui Aimin, as of the end of August this year, China had concluded visa exemption agreements with 14 countries covering ordinary passport holders.
In addition, more and more countries are unilaterally granting entry facilitation such as visa-free or visa-on-arrival to Chinese citizens.
42 countries and regions, including Thailand and Egypt, unilaterally granted visas on arrival to Chinese citizens holding ordinary passports, and 15 countries and regions, including Indonesia, unilaterally allowed visa-free entry for Chinese citizens holding ordinary passports.
In addition to visa-free and visa-on-arrival arrangements, it is becoming more and more convenient for Chinese citizens to apply for visas, and the procedures are becoming more and more simplified.
As of the end of August, China had reached agreements or arrangements with 41 countries to simplify visa procedures.
These include the 10-year multiple-entry visas issued to tourists and business personnel with the United States, Canada, Israel and Argentina, and the two-year multiple-entry visa arrangement with the United Kingdom for each other's tourism, business and family visitors.
The United Kingdom and Belgium jointly launched a "one-stop shop for visas", while France, Italy and Singapore have shortened the visa processing time to 48 hours, 36 hours and 24 hours respectively.
For business people who often go abroad, the APEC business travel card with multiple entries and convenient customs clearance is a good choice.
According to Cui Aimin, holding the travel card is equivalent to obtaining a five-year multiple visa for 16 economies around the Asia-Pacific region, which is of great significance to business personnel, especially those of private enterprises, to "go global".
At present, China ranks first among APEC economies in terms of the number of valid card holders.
The Ministry of Foreign Affairs will actively negotiate bilateral visa reciprocity agreements, encourage more countries to adopt visa facilitation measures for Chinese citizens, so that more diplomatic achievements can be translated into measures to benefit the people and facilitate the people, and continuously improve the 'gold content' of Chinese passports.
