The British-flagged Stena Impero tanker was seized by Iran in July.
A spokesman for the company said the tanker was preparing to leave Bandar Abbas.
Two weeks after Britain seized an Iranian oil tanker off the coast of Gibraltar, Iran's Revolutionary Guard Corps detained the tanker, called Stena Impero, in the Strait of Hormuz waterway.
The ship was released in August.
Earlier this week, an Iranian government spokesman said all legal procedures needed to release the Stana Empire had been completed.
But Iran said the investigation was still ongoing.
A number of Iranian media outlets have also published videos of the tanker setting sail.
On July 19, Iran's Islamic Revolutionary Guard Corps Navy detained a British oil tanker, the Stana Empire, in Iranian waters in the Strait of Hormuz and escorted it to Bandar Abbas.
The Iranian seized oil tanker Grace 1 sailed off the coast of Gibraltar.
In addition, on July 4, authorities in Gibraltar, a British overseas territory, seized the oil tanker Grace 1 loaded with Iranian crude oil in the Strait of Gibraltar on suspicion of transporting oil to Syria in violation of EU sanctions.
A little more than a month later, on 15 August, the Gibraltar authorities announced the release of Grace I.
